{{For|the waterpark in Ohio|The Beach at Adventure Landing}} {{Infobox amusement park | name = The Beach | image = [[File:The Beach logo.png|188px]] | caption = | location = [[Albuquerque, New Mexico|Albuquerque]] | location2 = [[New Mexico]] | location3 = United States | coordinates = {{coord|35.13233|-106.613087|type:landmark_region:US-NM|display=inline,title}} | address = 1600 Desert Surf Cir NE | opening_date = 1987 | closing_date = 2005 | water_rides = 10 }} '''The Beach''' was a 14-acre [[water park]] in [[Albuquerque]], [[New Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buildnewmexico.org/projects/Beach.html |title=Build New Mexico History |website=buildnewmexico.org/ |publisher=Build New Mexico |accessdate=August 2, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Carr2010">{{cite book|author=Debora L. Carr|title=Home on the Strange: More Tales from My Albu-Quirky Journals|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uScvU1LpRpsC&pg=PA15|date=April 2010|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|isbn=978-1-60844-458-8|pages=15–}}</ref><ref name="CommerceEvans2000">{{cite book|author1=Greater Albuquerque Chamber of Commerce|author2=Max Evans|title=Albuquerque: Spirit of the New West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6vqb_ldWGdUC|date=1 March 2000|publisher=Starlight Publishing|isbn=978-0-9639731-1-5}}</ref> The park was started in 1987, its final open season was 2004, and it was closed in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lane |first=Charlotte Balcomb |date=June 3, 2005 |title=All Dried Up: Beach Waterpark shuttered and for sale |url=http://abqjournal.com/paperboy/text/news/metro/357596metro06-03-05.htm |newspaper=[[Albuquerque Journal]] |location=Albuquerque, New Mexico |accessdate= August 2, 2014 }}</ref> The park's land was put up for sale in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Scott |first=Damon |date=Apr 29, 2014 |title=Former Beach Waterpark land listed for sale |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/albuquerque/news/2014/04/29/former-beach-waterpark-land-listed-for-sale.html |newspaper=Albuquerque Business Journal |location=Albuquerque, New Mexico |accessdate= August 2, 2014 }}</ref> When the park was active, the three 75-foot slides used to tower over [[Interstate 25]].<ref name="Goldsmith 2015">{{cite web | last=Goldsmith | first=Alex | title=Beach water park site could get new life soon | website=KRQE News 13 | date=February 9, 2015 | url=http://krqe.com/2015/02/08/beach-water-park-site-could-get-new-life-soon/ | accessdate=February 15, 2015}}</ref>
== Attractions == *Wave Pool – the main feature of the park was a 700,000 gallon pool that generated ocean-like waves. *Kiddie Pool – a miniature version of the park for kids, it had slides, a kiddie lazy river, a waterfall, a water umbrella, and a big purple dinosaur *Lazy River – a tube-ride river like oval that circled the vast majority of the park, it had multiple stops, at the kiddie pool, wave pool, slides, bathhouse and an ice cream shop. *4 and 8 Foot Tube-Slides – these were both slides that ran downhill. The four foot slide was a narrower slide with a faster current, the eight foot slide was a wider slide with a slower current. *The Silver Bullet - a body-slide that accommodated smaller children than their tower slides. *The Black Hole - a body-slide that was encompassed by a darkened tunnel, it led to a 3-foot deep catch pool. *The Plunge - a 75-foot "free-fall style" body-slide that led to a 3-foot deep catch pool. *The Scream – a 75-foot open slide with less-intense drop than The Plunge. *The Rolling Thunder - a 75-foot fully enclosed body slide with twists and turns.
